Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.39,0:00:12.22,Default,,0,0,0,,There wasn’t any resistance.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.26,0:00:14.26,Default,,0,0,0,,We didn’t have to force our way in.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.32,0:00:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,We simply drove in.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.70,0:00:19.50,Default,,0,0,0,,There was just this big gate.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.54,0:00:22.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And we opened it.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.12,0:00:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The first thing I saw were the barracks, but no people.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.60,0:00:28.98,Default,,0,0,0,,They were hiding.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.98,0:00:33.66,Default,,0,0,0,,They still didn’t know the war was over.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.32,0:00:43.08,Default,,0,0,0,,I didn't really understand that we were liberated.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.08,0:00:45.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Not until the war was over.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.78,0:00:50.90,Default,,0,0,0,,I didn’t have any sense of real happiness.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.90,0:00:54.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I felt alone, \Nin every way.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.66,0:01:00.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe it would’ve been different\Nif my parents had still been with me.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.06,0:01:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Thomas Bürgenthal is a child, \Njust 10 years old.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.38,0:01:17.24,Default,,0,0,0,,He arrives at Sachsenhausen\N having already come a long way.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.28,0:01:22.56,Default,,0,0,0,,For four long years,\Nhe and his family are stuck  in the Kielce Ghetto.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.60,0:01:30.56,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1944, he is deported to Auschwitz-Birkenau \Nand separated from his parents.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.56,0:01:34.32,Default,,0,0,0,,In January 1945, \NAuschwitz is evacuated.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.34,0:01:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Joining the children’s section of the death march, \NThomas walks for days through ice and snow.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.66,0:01:43.98,Default,,0,0,0,,A train finally brings them to Oranienburg.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.98,0:01:48.80,Default,,0,0,0,,His feet are half-frozen as he enters the camp,\N just outside town.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.80,0:01:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,During these days, \Nmany transports arrive at Sachsenhausen.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.62,0:01:55.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The camp is hopelessly overcrowded.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.22,0:01:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Up to a hundred inmates die every day.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.72,0:02:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Thomas Bürgenthal is in a great deal of pain.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.00,0:02:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The toes of his right foot are getting darker and darker.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.16,0:02:08.80,Default,,0,0,0,,He is sent to the infirmary.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.90,0:02:15.12,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s afraid of this facility, \Nbecause at Auschwitz it was the most certain way to the gas chamber.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.90,0:02:20.10,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s told to remove his shoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.10,0:02:22.50,Default,,0,0,0,,A doctor examines his feet.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.50,0:02:26.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The boy is laid on a wooden table.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.04,0:02:29.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Two men come over and grab his arms and legs.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.92,0:02:32.48,Default,,0,0,0,,They hold him down.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.48,0:02:34.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Thomas starts screaming.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.50,0:02:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,They put a white cloth over his face \Nand he quickly loses consciousness.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.82,0:02:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,When he wakes up, \Nhe’s in a sickroom.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.14,0:02:49.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Two toes from his right foot have been amputated.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.54,0:03:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Bernhard Storch swears to give his life \Nfor Poland in the battle against the German army.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.06,0:03:16.26,Default,,0,0,0,,He swears absolute loyalty to the Soviet Union\N in the fight against their common enemy.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.64,0:03:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Bernhard Storch is 16 when the Germans invade Poland.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.30,0:03:26.06,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s Jewish.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.10,0:03:31.38,Default,,0,0,0,,He escapes the looming persecution and goes to the Soviet Union.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.38,0:03:37.78,Default,,0,0,0,,There, in the spring of 1943, \Nhe joins a Polish unit of the Red Army.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.82,0:03:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,He believes this to be his only way back home.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.34,0:03:46.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Their division includes more than twelve thousand men.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.62,0:03:49.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Storch joins the artillery.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.70,0:03:53.28,Default,,0,0,0,,He enters the war with the Belorussian Front.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.52,0:04:00.12,Default,,0,0,0,,As they advance, \Nthey follow a trail of devastation and horror.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.16,0:04:06.98,Default,,0,0,0,, In a forest, they discover a railway track \Nwhich leads them to a place called Sobibor.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.00,0:04:08.92,Default,,0,0,0,,But there’s nothing there.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.96,0:04:14.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Only bare soil with a few trees, \Nand not a single soul.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.05,0:04:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s no one around \Nwho could tell them what happened here.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.06,0:04:24.44,Default,,0,0,0,,They have no time to stop somewhere, \Nno time to think.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.46,0:04:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The war’s imperatives push them onwards.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.98,0:04:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,They reach Majdanek.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.72,0:04:33.34,Default,,0,0,0,,This place of horror has also been abandoned.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.40,0:04:42.56,Default,,0,0,0,,They find thousands of suitcases and mountains of shoes, \Nand Storch fears that the personal effects might include those of his family,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.61,0:04:45.80,Default,,0,0,0,,whose whereabouts are unknown to him.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.86,0:04:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,They move on.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.28,0:04:50.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Storch looks down at himself.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.22,0:04:51.80,Default,,0,0,0,,He sees his shoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.84,0:04:53.62,Default,,0,0,0,,They’re all white.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.66,0:05:00.32,Default,,0,0,0,,White from the crematorium ashes\Nthat are scattered over the surrounding fields.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.70,0:05:09.92,Default,,0,0,0,,In April 1945, \NStorch’s division reaches the Oder river.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.96,0:05:18.46,Default,,0,0,0,,He sees how the river is filled with soldiers’ blood, and bodies, \Nbut must keep advancing without looking back.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.50,0:05:22.90,Default,,0,0,0,,At the same time,\Nthings are getting worse around Oranienburg too.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.92,0:05:28.90,Default,,0,0,0,, In March and April 1945, \Nthe town is heavily bombarded by air.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.94,0:05:32.84,Default,,0,0,0,,The front line is getting closer.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.88,0:05:41.14,Default,,0,0,0,,With the Battle of the Seelow Heights, \Nthe Red Army begins its final push: {\i1}The Berlin Offensive{\i0}.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.18,0:05:48.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Nearby at Sachsenhausen Concentration Camp, \NThomas Bürgenthal hears the Allied bombers.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.40,0:05:51.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Lying in the infirmary barracks, \Nhe dreams himself away.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.30,0:06:04.56,Default,,0,0,0,,He imagines one of the big planes coming down and lifting\Nthe barracks with a big hook, taking it away to England or America.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.58,0:06:09.14,Default,,0,0,0,,One morning, \Nthe sun is shining through the infirmary’s small window.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.16,0:06:11.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Thomas Bürgenthal wakes up.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.08,0:06:13.58,Default,,0,0,0,,He limps out onto the muster ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.62,0:06:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s completely empty!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.38,0:06:18.42,Default,,0,0,0,,The SS has evacuated the camp.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.42,0:06:21.96,Default,,0,0,0,,He looks up at the balcony of the administration building.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.00,0:06:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s no longer anyone behind the big machine gun.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.16,0:06:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The other watchtowers too: abandoned.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.42,0:06:34.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Suddenly he hears a creaking sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.46,0:06:37.94,Default,,0,0,0,,The big gate is opening.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.94,0:06:41.78,Default,,0,0,0,,He sees some soldiers getting out of a military vehicle.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.82,0:06:44.32,Default,,0,0,0,,They don’t look like SS.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.36,0:06:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,They’ve got uniforms he’s never seen before.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.80,0:06:54.08,Default,,0,0,0,,And then the camp’s bell starts ringing.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.12,0:07:00.34,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the soldiers is striking it with all his strength \Nwhile another shouts across the muster ground:
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.60,0:07:03.28,Default,,0,0,0,,{\i1}‘Hitler kaput! Hitler kaput!’{\i0}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.40,0:07:18.66,Default,,0,0,0,,When Bernhard Storch enters the camp, \Nhe doesn’t see the inmates right away.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.72,0:07:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,They stay in their barracks and hide.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.57,0:07:26.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But then they’re there.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.02,0:07:30.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the first time\Nthat they’re liberating people.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.30,0:07:37.96,Default,,0,0,0,,There are thousands of them, including many women,\Nwith wretched clothes and shorn hair.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.00,0:07:41.26,Default,,0,0,0,,They’re hardly recognizable as human beings.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.30,0:07:43.92,Default,,0,0,0,,They weep unceasingly.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.10,0:07:51.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The liberators distribute water among the prisoners\Nand assure them that their troubles are over.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.90,0:07:54.98,Default,,0,0,0,,They are free.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.52,0:08:08.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Thomas Bürgenthal roams the camp \Nand discovers an unlocked office.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.18,0:08:12.04,Default,,0,0,0,,A portrait of Hitler hangs above the desk.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.08,0:08:15.96,Default,,0,0,0,,He climbs up and tears down the picture.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.96,0:08:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,He dashes it on the floor.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.86,0:08:21.08,Default,,0,0,0,,The frame breaks and the glass shatters.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.14,0:08:27.86,Default,,0,0,0,,He spits on it and tramples Hitler’s face with such rage that his feet hurt,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.86,0:08:32.82,Default,,0,0,0,,but he keeps going until the picture is in tatters.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.54,0:08:45.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Thomas Bürgenthal leaves Oranienburg with the Polish Kościuszko Division. \NIt’s in Berlin that he sees the end of the war.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.50,0:08:49.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They take him to a Jewish orphanage near Warsaw.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.00,0:08:52.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Bürgenthal’s father is murdered at the camp in Flossenbürg.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.50,0:09:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,His mother Gerda survives, and after several months, she finds her son in Poland.\NThey move to Göttingen. In 1951, Bürgenthal emigrates to the USA.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.00,0:09:05.25,Default,,0,0,0,,After the fall of Berlin,\NBernhard Storch returns to Poland in search of his family.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.25,0:09:11.25,Default,,0,0,0,,They’re all dead.Their home is destroyed. \NHe never returns to his home town again.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.25,0:09:15.25,Default,,0,0,0,,In September 1945, he marries his wife Ruth in Katowice. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.25,0:09:20.30,Default,,0,0,0,,In April 1947, with two suitcases and $20, they board a ship for New York.
